fix(tui): clear primary device callback before invoking it (#34032)

A primary device callback may set a new callback (e.g. when suspending),
so clearing it after invoking it is too late.

While at it, add missing reset of did_set_grapheme_cluster_mode in
terminfo_start().

fix(extui): better message highlighting after carriage return (#34034)

Problem:  Incorrect message highlighting for highlighted message
          chunks containing carriage returns.
Solution: Add a highlight for each substring ending in a newline or
          carriage return separately.

fix(tui): feature detect vsplit scrolling in xterm-like terminals

Current "patch" asserts that EVERY terminal claiming to be an xterm has
broken vertical split scrolling which is far too an aggressive
workaround.

Instead, as left-right margins for scrolling regions use a
private DEC mode, we can use feature detection to use them in supported
terminals only. This way, users who use properly implemented terminals
can enjoy hardware accelerated scrolling even with vertical split
windows.

refactor(tui): remove obsolete can_set_left_right_margin duplicate

According to terminfo(5), these are obsolete:

Except for very old terminal descriptions, e.g., those developed
for SVr4, the scheme just described should be considered obsolete.
An improved set of capabilities was added late in the SVr4
releases (smglr and smgtb), which explicitly use two parameters
for setting the left/right or top/bottom margins.

vim-patch:9.1.1393: missing test for switching buffers and reusing curbuf

Problem:  The check in buf_freeall that restores curwin subtly prevents
          leaving an unloaded buffer in a window when reusing curbuf, if
          autocommands switch to a different buffer.
Solution: Add a test case that covers this. Also ensure splitting isn't
          possible, as that could do the same (Sean Dewar)

Problem:  search_stat not reset when pattern differs in case
          (tahzibijafar)
Solution: use STRNCMP instead of MB_STRNICMP macro

There was a long standing todo comment, that using MB_STRNICMP is wrong.
So let's change it to STRNCMP() instead. Even if it not handle
multi-byte characters correctly, then Vim will rather recompute the
search stat, instead of re-using the old (and possibly wrong) value.

fix(extui): translate <Tab> in cmdline text (#34055)

Problem:  <Tab> is not translated on the cmdline, and exposes a wrong
          assumption in search messages that may contain multiple chunks.
Solution: Translate unprintable characters in the cmdline content.
          Extract the 'search_count' from the last chunk and route
          'search_cmd' to cmdline to handle multiple chunks.

refactor(helptags): remove useless homegrown encoding check

This check was always broken. it will "detect" a file as
other-than-UTF-8 if the first line of a help file only is ASCII.

This only works by accident, as all our help files are UTF-8 (or
ASCII-only, which is fully compatible), but are all ASCII-only
on the first line of every help file which means that all helpfiles
gets detected as not-UTF8 which makes the "consistency" test pass
by accident even though the actual consistency is that every single
file is UTF-8 compatible. This means that the
"!_TAG_FILE_ENCODING\tutf-8\t" meta-tag already did not get emitted
but YAGNI in either case as no encoding tag just means that 'encoding'
is used which in neovim always is UTF-8 anyway.

An alternative approach would be to integrate the real encoding
detection already present in the codebase (an editor which edits text of
various encodings) which checks the entire file instead of a weird
first-line-only-hack, but as it happens to be 2025 the resolution of
encoding trouble is to just use UTF-8 everywhere. And if you use something
else you have to keep track yourself anyway it is not like we can detect
if one helpfile of your plugin is latin-1 and another is latin-2 or
whatever. Also, Nvim will detect the encoding of the file when you open
the file as a :help buffer anyway.

issue.title: Pre-Import Database Audit: Essential Tables & Indexes for 1M+ Movie Import
issue.body:
# Pre-Import Database Audit: Essential Tables & Indexes for 1M+ Movie Import

## Summary
Before importing 1M+ movies, we need to add several critical tables and indexes to ensure all features (especially Six Degrees of Separation and collaboration tracking) work efficiently and can be populated during import rather than requiring expensive rebuilds later.

## Critical Missing Tables

### 1. User & Social Features (Required for engagement tracking)
- [ ] **users** table - Basic user accounts for tracking preferences
- [ ] **user_watchlists** - Movies users want to watch
- [ ] **user_ratings** - User ratings for movies (separate from external ratings)
- [ ] **user_favorites** - Favorite movies/people/lists
- [ ] **user_follows** - Following other users, lists, or topics
- [ ] **user_preferences** - Discovery preferences, genre weights, etc.

### 2. Enhanced Collaboration Tables
- [ ] **collaboration_scores** - Pre-calculated collaboration quality scores
- [ ] **collaboration_network_cache** - Pre-computed network connections for fast Six Degrees queries
- [ ] **person_career_metrics** - Career phase tracking (early/peak/late) for better collaboration analysis
- [ ] **frequent_collaborators** - Pre-computed frequent collaborator pairs with stats

### 3. Movie Relationships & Series Tracking
- [ ] **movie_sequels** - Direct sequel/prequel relationships (not just collection_id)
- [ ] **movie_remakes** - Remake/original movie relationships
- [ ] **movie_adaptations** - Book/play/game adaptations tracking
- [ ] **franchise_timeline** - Chronological order within franchises
- [ ] **movie_influences** - Influenced by/influences relationships between movies

### 4. Performance & Prediction Tables
- [ ] **prediction_scores** - Pre-calculated prediction scores for awards/lists
- [ ] **prediction_history** - Track prediction accuracy over time
- [ ] **metric_scores** - Materialized metric scores for fast queries (currently only a view)
- [ ] **aggregated_person_stats** - Pre-aggregated person statistics

### 5. Enhanced Six Degrees Support
- [ ] **path_cache** - Cache calculated paths between people
- [ ] **connection_strength** - Pre-computed connection strength between all person pairs
- [ ] **degree_distribution** - Pre-computed degree distribution for network analysis
- [ ] **collaboration_clusters** - Identified collaboration clusters/communities

## Critical Missing Indexes

### 1. Composite Indexes for Complex Queries


### 2. Partial Indexes for Common Filters


### 3. GIN/GIST Indexes for JSONB and Arrays


## Data Import Considerations

### 1. Batch Processing Strategy
- Import movies in batches of 10,000
- Process collaborations after each batch
- Update person_relationships incrementally
- Build path_cache progressively

### 2. Parallel Processing Opportunities
- Calculate collaboration scores in parallel
- Build person metrics concurrently
- Pre-compute prediction scores asynchronously

### 3. Memory Management
- Use database-level materialized views for heavy computations
- Implement incremental refresh strategies
- Set up proper vacuum and analyze schedules

## Migration Strategy

### Phase 1: Core Tables (Before Import)
1. Add user tables (can be empty initially)
2. Add collaboration enhancement tables
3. Add critical indexes
4. Add movie relationship tables

### Phase 2: During Import
1. Populate collaboration tables as movies are imported
2. Build person_relationships incrementally
3. Calculate basic scores and metrics

### Phase 3: Post-Import Optimization
1. Build materialized views
2. Calculate prediction scores
3. Optimize queries based on actual data distribution

## Performance Impact Estimates

- **Six Degrees queries**: From O(n¬≤) to O(log n) with proper caching
- **Collaboration lookups**: 100x faster with pre-computed scores
- **Discovery queries**: 50x faster with proper indexes
- **Prediction calculations**: Near-instant with pre-computed scores

## Implementation Priority

1. **CRITICAL**: Collaboration enhancement tables (for Six Degrees feature)
2. **HIGH**: Performance indexes
3. **MEDIUM**: User/social tables (can be added later but better now)
4. **LOW**: Prediction history tables (can be added post-import)

## Next Steps

1. Review and approve table additions
2. Create migration files for new tables
3. Plan index creation strategy (some can be added after import)
4. Set up batch import infrastructure
5. Configure monitoring for import process

## Notes

- All foreign keys should have proper ON DELETE CASCADE
- Consider partitioning for tables that will exceed 100M rows
- Plan for regular VACUUM and ANALYZE during import
- Set up monitoring for index bloat and table statistics

issue.title: fix(discussions): find closest discussion comment or reply by timestamp
issue.body:
**Problem**
Earlier today I noticed several discussion notifications which were showing an incorrect actor profile image, and upon notification interaction deep-linking to the wrong discussion item (latest comment instead of most recent reply on an older comment thread).

**Solution**
Updating our logic to find the latest discussion comment or reply to instead find the closest/nearest in timestamp. 

In order to increase the accuracy, we have to fetch a wider selection of comments or replies before filtering down

I have a private Github repo that has some old secrets exposed. Among those are some unexpired JWTs that are picked up by the `--only-valid` flag so I wanted to establish a baseline.
